<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A transaction based system? That is usually reserved for the financial sector. Those are high dollar systems. The CPU overhead on a transaction based system is 10 times over non transaction based system.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The fact that this is a transaction based system has nothing to do with the size of the hardware. A $10,000.00 Dell server running MS SQL server or a Sun 15000 with 106 CPU's and Oracle Enterprise can both be transactional based systems. EQ is transactional because the data is constantly changing. What I'm talking about is process not necessarily more expensive hardware.<br>
<br>
Let's take a look at what I'm talking about. Every EQ character is saved on the world server every 5 minutes or whenever a trade is made between characters. That data is then saved on that particular server, and it appears that they then do a tape backup once a day of that data. This is where the problem begins. In a typical transaction based system you also have transaction logs in addition to the normal daily backups. SOE could improve this process by doing a couple of things. One they could save the incremental logs to a separate server that rolls over once the physical backups are completed. They could centralize their storage on one platform and now with the availability of ATA drives as second tier storage that is relatively cheap, they could do hourly snapshots of their data, Snapshots from most vendors only takes 20 percent of the original data size. There are many things they could do that would improve their Disaster recovery process without spending millions of dollars on infrastructure. <p>Maleador<br>
